  chapters:
  - verses:
    - name: '1-2: Tragedy Comes to a Family'
      title: Tragedy Comes to a Family
      number: 1-2
      content: 'During the era when champion-deliverers ruled in Israel, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        a severe famine overtook the land. Elimelech,  a man of importance,  left
        Bethlehem and immigrated to the country  of Moab. He took with him his wife
        Naomi  and their two sons, Mahlon  and Chilion.  They belonged to the clan
        of Ephrath from Bethlehem in Judah. While residing in Moab, '
      comments:
      - number: "1:1\u20132"
        content: "  The period of the champion-deliverers, or judges, covered about
          three hundred years (1400\u20131100 BC).        means \u201Cmy God is King.\u201D
          He was a descendant of Nahshon, a prince of the tribe of Judah (see  ),
          and an ancestor of David. Elimelech takes his family and leaves the \u201Chouse
          of bread\u201D (Bethlehem).      The Hebrew word    means \u201Ca certain
          man.\u201D In Rabbinic literature,    refers to a man of importance either
          in learning or in social status (i.e., a wealthy man).      Or \u201Cfields
          of Moab.\u201D Moab was the son of Lot\u2019s incestuous relationship with
          his daughter (see  ). Moab and his tribe lived east of the Dead Sea.       
          means \u201Cpleasant,\u201D \u201Cgracious,\u201D \u201Csweet,\u201D \u201Cagreeable,\u201D
          \u201Cdelightful,\u201D and \u201Cunsurpassed in beauty.\u201D        means
          \u201Cill [sickly],\u201D \u201Cworn out,\u201D \u201Cafflicted,\u201D
          or \u201Cwounded.\u201D Ruth was married to Mahlon, a picture of the law
          that is unable to save us (see  ;  ;  ;  ;  ). But Ruth (and we) will find
          another spouse (Boaz/Jesus).        means \u201Cdestruction\u201D or \u201Cconsumption.\u201D    "
