    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Elimelech died and left his widow Naomi alone with her two sons. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'The two sons both married Moabite [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>, who
        excludes such persons through sin, that will welcome through his abounding
        love and kindness the very ones he excluded. And</smallcaps><smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps> women, Orpah  and Ruth.  About ten years later, '
      comments:
      - number: 1:4
        content: "  According to  , the Israelites were not to marry with the Moabites,
          and the people of God were never to welcome the Moabites\u2019 descendants
          into their families. However, it is the graciousness of    would go further
          in that this family line would include David, Solomon, and Jesus, and thus
          establish an eternal throne and home by turning the cursed into the blessed.     
          , a homonym, can mean either \u201Cfawn\u201D or \u201C[back of the] neck.\u201D
          The proper name Orpah sounds like the Hebrew word for \u201Crebellious.\u201D
          Orpah turned her back on Naomi and returned to her home. Orpah was a good
          woman but not as faithful and resolute as Ruth.      The Hebrew name   
          has many possible meanings, including \u201Cclose friend,\u201D \u201Cneighbor,\u201D
          \u201Cshepherdess,\u201D \u201Cbeautiful,\u201D \u201Cdelightful,\u201D
          \u201Cpleasing,\u201D and \u201Csatisfied.\u201D    also sounds like the
          Hebrew word for \u201Crefreshing.\u201D The name Ruth occurs 12 times in
          this book. However, the Hebrew word    (or a variant form) is used 187
          times in the Old Testament. See also  .    "
    - name: '5: Naomi and Ruth Return to Bethlehem'
      title: Naomi and Ruth Return to Bethlehem
      number: 5
      content: Mahlon and Chilion also died and left Naomi all alone without husband
        or sons.
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'Sometime later, Naomi heard that <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> had
        visited his people and blessed them with an abundant harvest; [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps><smallcaps>  </smallcaps><smallcaps>, who still brings sunrise
        and rainfall to all, whether they do good or evil (see</smallcaps><smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps> so she decided to leave Moab with her daughters-in-law. '
      comments:
      - number: 1:6
        content: "  Or \u201Chad visited [observed, taken note of] his people and
          given them food.\u201D It is notable that, while in the law, famine is
          attributed to unfaithfulness and fruitfulness to faithfulness, here  simply
          blessed the people in the days of the judges when everyone did whatever
          they wanted to do. This reveals the mercies of    ). The theme of the goodness
          and faithfulness of  runs throughout this book.    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'With Orpah and Ruth at her side, Naomi began her journey to return
        to the land of Judah. '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "But soon Naomi said to them, \u201CEach of you, go back to your mother\u2019s
        home. May <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> show his loyal love and kindness
        to you\u2014the same loyal love and kindness you\u2019ve shown to me and
        to those who have died. "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "And may <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> give you another husband and
        cause you to find rest in a happy home.\u201DThen Naomi tenderly embraced
        Orpah and Ruth and kissed them goodbye, but they wailed and sobbed. "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "Through their tears, they said to her, \u201CNo! We want to be with
        you and go with you to your people.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "\u201CMy daughters, you must go back,\u201D Naomi answered. \u201CWhy
        do you want to come with me? Do you think I could have sons again to give
        you new husbands? [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 1:11
        content: '  Naomi was referring to the law of levirate marriage, where the
          next closest relative marries a widow to produce a child and heir for the
          deceased husband so that their inheritance will not be lost.    '
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Turn around my daughters and go back home, for I\u2019m too old to
        marry again. Even if I thought there was still hope for me, and married today
        and gave birth to sons, "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "would you wait until they had grown up? Should you live for so many
        years without husbands? No, my daughters, you must not return with me. My
        life is too bitter for you to share it with me because <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        has brought calamity to my life!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>  </smallcaps>"
      comments:
      - number: 1:13
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe hand of  has gone out against me.\u201D    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "When they heard Naomi\u2019s words, Orpah and Ruth wailed and sobbed
        again. Then Orpah embraced and kissed her mother-in-law goodbye and went
        back home, [[COMMENT(0)]] but Ruth clung tightly to Naomi and refused to
        let go of her.   "
      comments:
      - number: 1:14
        content: "  Orpah never saw the face of her kinsman-redeemer. She died as
          she lived\u2014in Moab. See  ;  .      The Hebrew verb for \u201Ccling
          tightly\u201D is  . It carries the sense of permanent bonding (as with
          adhesive). The term is used in the Bible for covenantal devotion and clinging
          to God or a person. Loaded with spiritual meaning to a Hebrew speaker,
          this is the major term for spiritual cleaving to God in Rabbinic literature.
          In a sense, Ruth was entering into a covenant with Naomi. The Targum states,
          using several sources, that Ruth truly desired to be a proselyte to the
          Jewish faith. (See  ;  ; and    on  .) The Jewess Naomi is a type of Israel,
          and the gentile Ruth is a type of the church. As Ruth stayed connected
          to Naomi (Israel), Naomi would lead her to Boaz (a type of our Kinsman-Redeemer,
          Jesus).    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "Naomi said, \u201CRuth, listen. Your sister-in-law is going back
        to Moab to her people and to her gods. [[COMMENT(0)]] Now go with her.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 1:15
        content: '  One of the gods of the Moabites was Chemosh (see  ;  ). On our
          road to full restoration, we all face a choice either to return to Judah
          (the land of praise) and to Boaz (Jesus) or to turn back to other gods
          and the old order.    '
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "But tearfully, Ruth insisted, \u201CPlease don\u2019t ask me again
        to leave you! I want to go with you and stay with you. Wherever you go, I
        will go; wherever you live, I will live. Your people will now be my people,
        and your God will now be my God. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 1:16
        content: "  See  ;  ;  ;  ;  . Ruth uses the name \u201CShaddai\u201D (the
          Almighty) for God.    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "Wherever you die, I will die there, too; [[COMMENT(0)]] that\u2019s
        where your people will bury me\u2014next to you. Nothing but death itself
        will separate me from you, so help me God!\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 1:17
        content: '  The old Ruth died. We, too, have been crucified with Christ.
          His cross was our cross (see  ;  ).    '
    - name: '18: Naomi Returns to Bethlehem with Ruth'
      title: Naomi Returns to Bethlehem with Ruth
      number: 18
      content: "When Naomi realized that Ruth\u2019s heart was set on going with
        her, she said nothing more."
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Naomi and Ruth traveled together from Moab until they came to Bethlehem.
        The entire town was buzzing [[COMMENT(0)]] when they heard they had arrived!
        Astounded, the women of the town said to one another, \u201CIs this really
        Naomi, who left us so long ago?\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 1:19
        content: "  Or \u201Cthey were beside themselves.\u201D    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "\u201CPlease don\u2019t call me Naomi anymore,\u201D she insisted.
        \u201CInstead, call me Marah, [[COMMENT(0)]] because Almighty God  has dealt
        me a bitter blow. "
      comments:
      - number: 1:20
        content: "  Or \u201CMara [a form of Miriam].\u201D    means \u201Cbitter.\u201D   
          means \u201Cpleasant.\u201D Life sometimes takes us from seasons of great
          pleasure into a wilderness where we drink \u201Cbitter waters.\u201D Yet
          in the wilderness, God will meet us and turn our bitterness into something
          sweet. See  ;  ;  .      Or \u201CShaddai.\u201D This name of God is found
          forty-eight times in the Bible, with thirty-one of them in Job and six
          in Genesis. It is the most frequently used name for God prior to Moses\u2019
          reception of the law at Sinai.    is taken from a Hebrew root word that
          carries multiple expressive meanings. It can mean \u201CGod of the holy
          mountain,\u201D \u201CGod of the wilderness,\u201D \u201CGod the destroyer
          of enemies,\u201D \u201CGod the all-sufficient One,\u201D \u201CGod the
          nurturer of babies [the breasted One],\u201D \u201CGod the almighty,\u201D
          \u201Cthe sovereign God,\u201D or \u201Cthe God who is more than enough.\u201D    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "When I left here, my heart was full [[COMMENT(0)]] and content with
        my family, but <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> has brought me back empty and
        destitute. Why call me by my name, \u2018Pleasant,\u2019 when <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        has opposed me, and Almighty God has brought me so much trouble?\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 1:21
        content: '  That is, blessed with husband and sons.    '
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'So Naomi returned to her village with Ruth, her Moabite daughter-in-law.
        [[COMMENT(0)]] They arrived in Bethlehem just as the barley harvest had begun. '
      comments:
      - number: 1:22
        content: "  Naomi\u2019s sojourn in Moab lasted about ten years.      The
          season of famine had ended, and the season of harvest had begun. In Israel,
          the harvest season for barley is from mid-March through mid-April, the
          time of the Feast of Passover.  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Ruth Gathers Grain in the Field of Boaz'
      title: Ruth Gathers Grain in the Field of Boaz
      number: 1
      content: "Naomi\u2019s deceased husband, Elimelech, had a very wealthy relative,
        an honorable and prominent man [[COMMENT(0)]] in Bethlehem named Boaz.   "
      comments:
      - number: 2:1
        content: "  The description \u201Chonorable and prominent\u201D comes from
          the Hebrew word  .    can also mean \u201Cvictorious,\u201D \u201Cpowerful,\u201D
          \u201Clike an army,\u201D or \u201Cfull of substance.\u201D Thus Boaz was
          a \u201Cmighty man of valor\u201D or \u201Cvaliant warrior.\u201D (We might
          say, \u201Ca knight in shining armor.\u201D)        means \u201Cstrength.\u201D
          He is a prophetic figure of Jesus Christ, our older Brother (see  ;  )
          and Kinsman-Redeemer (see  ). \u201CBoaz\u201D was also the name of the
          left pillar of Solomon\u2019s Temple (). Boaz was a wealthy nobleman. Similarly,
          Jesus Christ is indeed the One who has made us \u201Crich beyond measure\u201D
          (; see  ).    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "One day Ruth the Moabite said to Naomi, \u201CLet me go to the fields
        and pick up the leftover grain. Maybe someone will be kind enough [[COMMENT(0)]]
        to let me gather the grain he leaves behind.\u201DNaomi said to her, \u201CGo,
        my daughter.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 2:2
        content: "  Or \u201CMaybe I will find grace with someone.\u201D See  .    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'So Ruth went to the fields to gather the grain the reapers left behind.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>  </smallcaps> It just so happened  that she found
        herself working at the edges of a field belonging to Boaz  of the family
        of Elimelech. '
      comments:
      - number: 2:3
        content: "  That there was grain left behind for the poor to pick up speaks
          to the covenant faithfulness of Boaz, who had instructed his workers to
          keep the commandment to care for the poor according to  . God commanded
          this also to remind Israel that they were once slaves in Egypt who depended
          upon the generosity of  to feed them.      The Hebrew reads \u201Cher chance\u201D
          or \u201Cchanced.\u201D      The fields of Boaz may have included the shepherd\u2019s
          field where the angels of glory announced Jesus\u2019 birth. See  .    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "At that moment, Boaz came from Bethlehem to survey his harvest. He
        greeted the harvesters, \u201CMay <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> be with you.\u201D
        [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>\u2019s blessing indeed be upon them as they seek
        a global harvest of souls.</smallcaps> They replied, \u201CMay <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        bless you.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 2:4
        content: "  Jesus, too, came from Bethlehem to bless his harvesters. Today\u2019s
          \u201Charvesters\u201D are the evangelists who go to the nations of the
          earth to preach the gospel of Jesus Christ. May      "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Noticing Ruth, Boaz asked his foreman in charge of the harvesters,
        [[COMMENT(0)]] \u201CWho is that young woman over there?\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 2:5
        content: "  The Holy Spirit is the Lord of the Harvest who equips and places
          each believer in the harvest fields where we will be the most effective.
          See  .      Or \u201CTo whom does that young woman belong?\u201D Ruth could
          have been between twenty-four and twenty-nine years old at this time. Boaz
          may have been in his forties.    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "The foreman answered, \u201CShe\u2019s a Moabite girl who came back
        with Naomi from the country of Moab. "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "She asked for permission to gather the grain left behind by the reapers.
        Except for one short break, she\u2019s been on her feet working in the field
        since early this morning.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "Boaz walked over to Ruth and said, \u201CListen, my daughter, don\u2019t
        leave this field to glean somewhere else. Stay here in my field and follow
        the young women who work for me. "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Watch my harvesters to see into which fields they go to cut grain,
        and follow them. When you\u2019re thirsty, go and drink from the water jugs
        that the young men have filled. I\u2019ve warned the young men not to bother
        you.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "Astounded, Ruth bowed low with her face to the ground, and said to
        him, \u201CI\u2019m a foreigner. Why have you been so kind and taken notice
        of me?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Boaz answered, \u201CI\u2019ve heard all about what you\u2019ve done
        for your mother-in-law since the death of your husband. I know your story\u2014how
        you left your father and mother and your native land and came to a people
        and a culture that must seem strange to you. "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "May <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> reward you for your sacrifices,
        and because of what you\u2019ve done, may you have a full and rich reward
        from <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, the God of Israel, under whose wings
        you have come to find shelter!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "Ruth replied, \u201CMay I continue to find favor in your sight, kind
        sir. You have spoken to my heart kind and reassuring words that comfort me,
        even though I am not as worthy as one of your servant girls.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "At mealtime, Boaz said to her, \u201CCome here [[COMMENT(0)]] and
        eat with us. Here is bread, and wine to dip it in.\u201D  Ruth immediately
        sat down with the workers. Boaz handed her some roasted grain, and she ate
        all she wanted until she was satisfied\u2014she even had some left over."
      comments:
      - number: 2:14
        content: "  Or \u201Cdraw near.\u201D      Read this sentence again and picture
          Jesus, your heavenly Boaz, inviting you to have communion (bread and wine)
          with him.    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "After she had returned to gather grain, Boaz instructed his young
        men, \u201CLet her glean even among the standing sheaves, and don\u2019t
        disgrace her. "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "Pull out from the bundles some handfuls of grain and drop them on
        purpose [[COMMENT(0)]] for her to gather, and don\u2019t bother her.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 2:16
        content: "  These \u201Chandfuls of grain\u201D dropped \u201Con purpose\u201D
          can signify the many extra blessings that fall upon us each day. We gather
          truths from Scripture for our needs each day, like Ruth gathered grain
          (see  ). Jesus, our heavenly Boaz, drops handfuls of revelation on purpose
          for us to gather an abundant supply. He wants us to know that he will provide
          all we need to meet the challenges of life. See  ;  ;  ;  ;  .    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "So Ruth gathered grain in Boaz\u2019s field until evening. When she
        threshed out what she had gathered, it came to more than half a bushel of
        barley. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 2:17
        content: "  Or \u201Can ephah of barley.\u201D An ephah would weigh about
          thirty pounds.    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: She carried it back to town and showed her mother-in-law how much
        she had gleaned. Then Ruth also took out the roasted grain she had saved
        from mealtime and shared it with Naomi.
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Her mother-in-law asked Ruth, \u201CWhere did you gather all this
        from? In whose field did you work? May <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> bless
        the man who showed you special attention.\u201DShe told her mother-in-law
        about all that happened that day, and said, \u201CThe man in whose field
        I gathered grain today is Boaz.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "Naomi said to Ruth, \u201C<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s loving-kindness
        has not left us either through life or through death! Boaz is closely related
        to us. He is a kinsman-redeemer [[COMMENT(0)]] of our family. May <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> 
        greatly bless Boaz!\u201D <smallcaps>, whose loyal love has not forsaken
        the living or the dead.\u201D</smallcaps>"
      comments:
      - number: 2:20
        content: "  The Hebrew term    means \u201Ckinsman-redeemer.\u201D This term
          is used in various forms ten times throughout chs.  .    signifies a legal
          function performed by a near relative. If a widow was childless, a close
          male relative was empowered to \u201Credeem\u201D her through marriage
          and buy back her property (see  ). This kinsman-redeemer ensured that the
          widow would not lose her inheritance rights and provided her with offspring.
          In the case of Naomi, she had other near relatives living in Bethlehem
          who would qualify to be her kinsman-redeemers, meaning that Boaz was perhaps
          one of several candidates.      The Hebrew is somewhat ambiguous: \u201CMay
          he [Boaz] be blessed by    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "Ruth the Moabite responded, \u201CHe even said to me, \u2018Stay
        close by my servants until they have finished all my harvest.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "Naomi replied, \u201CIt is best, my daughter, that you stay near
        his young women, otherwise you\u2019ll be alone and might be bothered in
        someone else\u2019s field.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "So Ruth worked alongside the young women who served Boaz. She lived
        with her mother-in-law and gleaned in Boaz\u2019s fields until the end of
        the barley and wheat harvests."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Ruth and Boaz at the Threshing Floor'
      title: Ruth and Boaz at the Threshing Floor
      number: 1
      content: "One day, Naomi said to Ruth: \u201CI want to see you marry so that
        you\u2019ll be happy and secure. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 3:1
        content: "  The Hebrew text is literally \u201CShould I not seek rest [a
          home] for you so it may go well with you?\u201D    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "Now listen, a man named Boaz is our relative. [[COMMENT(0)]] You
        worked with his servant girls in his fields. This evening, he\u2019ll be
        winnowing barley on the threshing floor.   "
      comments:
      - number: 3:2
        content: "  Boaz is a picture of our Lord Jesus Christ. Jesus is our Kinsman-Redeemer.
          He is a kinsman, for he took upon himself flesh and blood to take away
          our curse (see  ;  ) and our slavery to sin. He is the appointed heir of
          all things (see  ). He has perpetuated the nature, character, and kingdom
          of God upon the earth. He has perpetuated God\u2019s name (see  ;  ).     
          Likewise, in the \u201Cevening\u201D of this age, our heavenly Boaz is
          at his threshing floor separating the chaff from the grain (see  ;  ; 
          ;  ).    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Now, take a bath and put on some nice perfume. [[COMMENT(0)]] Dress
        in your best clothes  and go to the threshing floor, but don\u2019t let him
        know you\u2019re there until he\u2019s had plenty to eat and drink. "
      comments:
      - number: 3:3
        content: "  Or \u201Canoint yourself.\u201D In this final season of harvest,
          we too are to wash ourselves by the Word of God (see  ;  ), and we also
          will receive the anointing of the Holy Spirit through prayer and devotion
          before the Lord.      The believer today wears their \u201Cbest clothes\u201D
          when putting on Christ (cf.  ). We are clothed in his perfect righteousness.
          Then we go down humbly to meet our Beloved at his threshing floor.    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Watch closely to see where he lies down. [[COMMENT(0)]] Then go,
        uncover his feet, and lie down there.  He will tell you what to do.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 3:4
        content: "  We need to note the place where our Boaz lay down (the cross
          and empty tomb). He lay down to rest in his finished work (see  ;  ).     
          Symbolically, we too uncover (reveal) his feet, his walk of holiness and
          love. We appropriate his grace to walk in his ways when we take our place
          resting with him in his finished work. We are a company of lovers resting
          at his feet\u2014\u201Ca feet company\u201D who will walk like him. All
          we have to do is listen and obey him, for he will tell us what to do (see 
          ). Jesus will have a loving bride worshiping at his feet at midnight.    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Ruth answered, \u201CI\u2019ll do everything you\u2019ve told me.\u201D
        [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 3:5
        content: "  Like Mary, the mother of Jesus, Ruth accepted what the Lord had
          for her. \u201CMay everything you have told me come to pass\u201D ().    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'That evening, Ruth went down to the threshing floor and did all her
        mother-in-law had told her to do. '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: After his evening meal, Boaz was in a good mood. He went to lie down
        at the far end of the grain pile [[COMMENT(0)]] and fell fast asleep. Ruth
        quietly tiptoed over to him, uncovered his feet, and lay down.
      comments:
      - number: 3:7
        content: "  At the end of this age there will be a great harvest, a \u201Cpile
          of grain\u201D brought to our Lord Jesus Christ.    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'Around midnight, Boaz was startled, and he awoke. He was surprised
        to find a woman lying at his feet. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "\u201CWho are you?\u201D Boaz asked.\u201CI am Ruth, your servant
        girl,\u201D she answered. \u201CSpread the corner [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps><smallcaps>  </smallcaps><smallcaps>\u2019s faithfulness. This
        same \u201Ccorner\u201D is the one that the woman with the issue of blood
        took hold of on Jesus\u2019 garment in</smallcaps><smallcaps>, the tassels
        at the edge of Jesus\u2019 garments conveyed the blessing of healing, in
        testimony to the faithfulness of</smallcaps><smallcaps>  </smallcaps> of
        your garment over me  because you are a close relative by marriage, one who
        is my kinsman-redeemer.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 3:9
        content: "  The garments of faithful Israelites included a tassel at each
          of the four corners according to  ;  . This was an outward sign of covenant
          faithfulness, which Ruth seemed to acknowledge when she asked Boaz to cover
          her with the \u201Ccorner\u201D of his garment. She knew him to be faithful
          to  in other ways, and in this fashion, she trusted he would be faithful
          to the covenant toward her and Naomi. Boaz would redeem what  sought to
          be redeemed, and Ruth was seeking the fulfillment of the promise to be
          \u201Cunder the wing\u201D of    . While the teachers of the law in Jesus\u2019
          day wore their tassels extra long, as if they were extra faithful to   
          himself.      Or \u201Cspread your wing [or wings] over me.\u201D This
          was likely a figure of speech for \u201CPlease marry me.\u201D Ruth\u2019s
          actions were symbolic of a marriage proposal. Jesus spreads his wings over
          us and heals us (see  ;  ). His mantle (cloak) of anointing covers us.     
          That is, \u201Cone who has the right to marry me.\u201D Ruth knew who she
          was. She boldly requested grace from Boaz. We too come boldly to the throne
          of grace. Ruth had no false humility; she was sincere and confident as
          she spoke to Boaz. She called herself his \u201Cservant.\u201D For the
          word \u201Cservant,\u201D the Greek Septuagint uses the word  , which means
          \u201Ca bondservant unto death.\u201D    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "Boaz said: \u201CDear woman, may <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> bless
        you, for this act of kindness you are showing me exceeds the kindness you
        have shown to Naomi. You didn\u2019t search for a young man to marry, either
        rich or poor. "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "My daughter, don\u2019t worry. I promise to do everything you ask,
        because everyone knows [[COMMENT(0)]] you\u2019re a brave woman of noble
        character.   "
      comments:
      - number: 3:11
        content: "  Ruth, the bride, could not hide her true character. See  ; cf. 
          .      Or \u201Cvirtuous woman.\u201D This is the Hebrew word  , which
          is often used in connection with military prowess and moral excellence.
          See the first footnote on  . We can see Ruth as a metaphor for the \u201Clast-days\u201D
          church, the virtuous, overcoming bride of Jesus Christ. See  .    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "It\u2019s true that I am a kinsman-redeemer, but you have a closer
        kinsman-redeemer than I. "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "Stay here tonight, [[COMMENT(0)]]  and I will protect you. In the
        morning, we\u2019ll see if he\u2019s willing to redeem you.  If he does,
        good; let him. But if he refuses to redeem you, then I promise, as surely
        as <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> lives, I will. Sleep here until morning.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 3:13
        content: "  Ruth rested at Boaz\u2019s feet through the dark night until
          morning. See  ;  ;  ;  ;  .      That is, \u201Cwe will see if he chooses
          to marry you.\u201D    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "So Ruth stayed near Boaz\u2019s feet that night. She awoke before
        it was light enough for anyone to recognize her. Boaz thought, \u201CNo one
        must know that a woman visited me at the threshing floor.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "As Ruth was about to leave, Boaz said to her, \u201CHere, bring me
        the cloak you\u2019re wearing and hold it open.\u201DAs she held it open,
        Boaz poured six measures [[COMMENT(0)]] of barley into it. He then helped
        place it on her head to carry, and she went back to Bethlehem."
      comments:
      - number: 3:15
        content: "  The Hebrew text does not state what measure is involved, but
          it had to be an amount that a woman could carry on her head or shoulder.
          The majority of modern scholars conclude that the amount of barley could
          have exceeded fifty pounds. If so, this impressive amount of barley was
          designed to impress both Ruth and Naomi with Boaz\u2019s generosity and
          his determination to help them.    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "When Ruth returned to her mother-in-law, Naomi asked her, \u201CHow
        did it go, my dear daughter? How did Boaz receive you?\u201DRuth told Naomi
        everything that he did for her. "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "She added, \u201CBoaz gave me all this barley, saying, \u2018You
        must not go home empty-handed without a gift for your mother in law.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Naomi answered, \u201CMy daughter, wait here until you see what happens.
        Boaz will not rest until he has finished [[COMMENT(0)]] doing what he promised
        he would do today.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 3:18
        content: "  Jesus has \u201Cfinished\u201D all he needed to do to redeem
          us fully. We rest from our own labors in his finished work. The Hebrew
          word for \u201Cfinished\u201D is  , which is a homonym of the word for
          \u201Cbride.\u201D See  .  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Boaz the Kinsman-Redeemer'
      title: Boaz the Kinsman-Redeemer
      number: 1
      content: "No sooner had Boaz gone up to the city gate and sat down [[COMMENT(0)]]
        when the kinsman-redeemer  of whom Boaz had spoken came passing by. Boaz
        called to him, \u201CCome over here, friend; sit down with me. We have some
        business to attend to.\u201D So the man went over and sat down."
      comments:
      - number: 4:1
        content: "  Jesus, our heavenly Boaz, went \u201Cup\u201D in his ascension
          and \u201Csat down\u201D at the right hand of God in glory.      This man
          was in the position to be a redeemer; however, in the context of the business
          at the gate, he had not yet exercised his right to redeem and thus had
          not yet become the kinsman-redeemer in fact. See vv.  ,  ,  .    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "Then Boaz invited ten [[COMMENT(0)]] men of the city council and
        said, \u201CPlease, sit down here with us.\u201D After they were seated, "
      comments:
      - number: 4:2
        content: '  The number ten is recognized biblically as the number of human
          responsibility (Ten Commandments). The law kept Ruth out (see  ). The law
          serves to add guilt to the human condition. Boaz prefigured Jesus, our
          gracious Kinsman-Redeemer, who has done for us what the law cannot (see 
          ;  ;  ).    '
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Boaz turned to the kinsman-redeemer and said, \u201CSir, Naomi has
        returned from the country of Moab, and she\u2019s selling the piece of property
        that belonged to our relative Elimelech. "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "So I thought you ought to know about it. [[COMMENT(0)]] Buy it if
        you want. We can make it official in the presence of those here and in the
        presence of the elders of our people. As the kinsman-redeemer, you have the
        first right of refusal. Redeem it if you choose to, but if not, tell me so
        I will know, as I am next in line.\u201DThe man replied, \u201CI\u2019ll
        redeem it.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 4:4
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Then Boaz added, \u201CThe day you buy the field from the hand of
        Naomi, you also acquire Ruth the Moabite, [[COMMENT(0)]] the widow of the
        dead.  Therefore, it will be your responsibility to father a child in order
        to maintain the dead man\u2019s name on his inheritance.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 4:5
        content: "  Boaz mentioned the land (field) before he mentioned Ruth (the
          treasure). Boaz was not afraid to pay the price to acquire both the field
          and the treasure. See  .      The law is weak and sickly, like Ruth\u2019s
          deceased husband, Mahlon (see  ;  ).    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "At this, the kinsman-redeemer balked and said, \u201CIn that case,
        I\u2019m not able to redeem it for myself without risking my own inheritance.
        Take my purchase option of redemption yourself, for I can\u2019t do it.\u201D
        [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>  </smallcaps><smallcaps>\u2019s faithfulness that
        we receive an eternal name and are placed as pillars in the temple of our
        God.</smallcaps>"
      comments:
      - number: 4:6
        content: "  The summary statement of the law is \u201CI can\u2019t do it.\u201D
          Grace, not law-keeping, is our only hope of salvation (see  ;  ). This
          man desired to preserve his name in Israel by not marrying the Moabite
          woman. However, his name has been lost. Boaz, on the other hand, not only
          preserved his name in this story that is read every year in the Jewish
          celebrations, but he also had his name inscribed upon the pillar in the
          temple of  built by Solomon. It is not in seeking to preserve our own name
          but seeking      "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: '(At that time in Israel, in order to finalize a transaction concerning
        redeeming and transferring property, a man would customarily remove a sandal
        [[COMMENT(0)]] and give it to the other party, making the contract legally
        binding.) '
      comments:
      - number: 4:7
        content: "  The sandal symbolized the man\u2019s property rights. To give
          up the sandal meant he would no longer walk on that property and claim
          it as his; he had transferred the rights to another. This custom had become
          obsolete by the time of writing, which shows that the book of Ruth was
          written well after the events of Ruth had transpired.    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "So when the kinsman-redeemer said to Boaz, \u201CTake my purchase
        option of redemption for yourself,\u201D he took off his sandal and gave
        it to Boaz. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 4:8
        content: "  Jesus received the rights (the sandal) to supersede the law and
          obtained the promise of a more excellent ministry than the law (see  ).
          We are his \u201Cseed\u201D and joint heirs of his ministry.    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Then Boaz turned to the elders and announced publicly, \u201CToday,
        you are witnesses that I have purchased from the hand of Naomi all that belonged
        to Elimelech and all that belonged to Chilion and Mahlon. "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "I have also acquired Ruth the Moabite, Mahlon\u2019s widow, to be
        my wife. I will raise children with her who will maintain the dead man\u2019s
        name on his inheritance so that the name of the dead may not be cut off from
        his village and from his family line. Today, you are witnesses of this transaction.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Then all the elders and all the people who were at the gate said:
        \u201CWe are witnesses. May <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> make the woman
        who is coming into your house like Rachel and Leah, both of whom built up
        the house of Israel. May you become famous in Bethlehem! May you become very
        prosperous! "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: Boaz and Ruth Marry'
      title: Boaz and Ruth Marry
      number: 12
      content: "And may <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> give you children by this young
        woman, and through them, may your family be like the family of Perez, whom
        Tamar bore to Judah!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>  </smallcaps>"
      comments:
      - number: 4:12
        content: "  The people of Bethlehem were recalling the story of Judah\u2019s
          sinning sons who did not have sons of their own through disobedience in 
          . Judah himself sinfully slept with his Canaanite daughter-in-law (thinking
          she was a prostitute). But what was sinful,  turned to goodness through
          redemption.    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "So Boaz and Ruth married, and they became one as husband and wife.
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> opened Ruth\u2019s womb, and she bore a son. "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Then the women of Bethlehem blessed Naomi: \u201CPraise <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        who never abandoned you nor withheld from you a kinsman-redeemer! And may
        his name be famous in Israel! [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 4:14
        content: "  Or \u201CMay his name be declared in Israel.\u201D    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "May this child renew your life and sustain you in your old age! May
        your daughter-in-law, who loves you dearly, be more to you than seven sons
        could ever be, for she has given you a wonderful grandchild!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'Then Naomi took her grandson and cuddled him in her arms and cared
        for him [[COMMENT(0)]] as if he were her own. '
      comments:
      - number: 4:16
        content: '  That is, Naomi became like a foster mother to Obed.    '
    - name: '17: The Genealogy of David'
      title: The Genealogy of David
      number: 17
      content: "The women of the neighborhood gave him a name, saying, \u201CAt last,
        Naomi has a son!\u201D They named him Obed, [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>].\u201D
        It is possibly a shortened form of Obadiah, which has the same meaning.</smallcaps>
        and he became the father of Jesse, the father of David."
      comments:
      - number: 4:17
        content: "  The name    means \u201Cworshiper\u201D or \u201Cservant [of      "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'Now these are the descendants of Perez: [[COMMENT(0)]]Perez became
        the father of Hezron,'
      comments:
      - number: 4:18
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: Hezron the father of Ram,Ram the father of Amminadab,
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: Amminadab the father of Nahshon,Nahshon the father of Salmon,
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: Salmon the father of Boaz,Boaz the father of Obed,
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: Obed the father of Jesse,who had a famous son, King David. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 4:22
        content: "  The story of Ruth shows that the family of David was in reality
          from Bethlehem and that David\u2019s great-grandmother was Ruth, a gentile
          from Moab.  "
